<item>
            <title>[LU-12912] fsck looping</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-12912</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;An OST on one of our systems went read-only last week. Today I unmounted the particular OST and ran a read-only fsck against the target. During the fsck the check got stuck on one inode and kept repeating the message:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Block &amp;lt;foo&amp;gt; (&amp;lt;bar&amp;gt;) causes symlink to be too big. IGNORE.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(repeats 12 times)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Too many illegal blocks in inode 33023185.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Clear inode? no&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Suppress message? no&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This continually repeats. Since it was a read-only fsck we terminated it and remounted the file system without going any further with the file system repair without consulting with you first.&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is on a classified system so providing explicit detail will be difficult. Note: This problem is similar to &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-12386&quot; title=&quot;ldiskfs-fs error: ldiskfs_iget:4374: inode #x: comm ll_ostx_y: bad extra_isize (36832 != 512)&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;LU-12386&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;LU-12386&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; that was posted last year.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
                <environment>DDN sfa12k IB attached to Dell R730 servers. TOSS 3.5.1 (rhel 7.5)/Lustre 2.10.5/e2fsprogs-1.42.13.wc6-7.el7.x86_64</environment>
        <key id="57259">LU-12912</key>
            <summary>fsck looping</summary>
                <type id="1" iconUrl="https://jira.whamcloud.com/secure/viewavatar?size=xsmall&amp;avatarId=11303&amp;avatarType=issuetype">Bug</type>
                                            <priority id="4" iconUrl="https://jira.whamcloud.com/images/icons/priorities/minor.svg">Minor</priority>
                        <status id="5" iconUrl="https://jira.whamcloud.com/images/icons/statuses/resolved.png" description="A resolution has been taken, and it is awaiting verification by reporter. From here issues are either reopened, or are closed.">Resolved</status>
                    <statusCategory id="3" key="done" colorName="success"/>
                                    <resolution id="1">Fixed</resolution>
                                        <assignee username="pjones">Peter Jones</assignee>
                                    <reporter username="jamervi">Joe Mervini</reporter>
                        <labels>
                    </labels>
                <created>Mon, 28 Oct 2019 21:30:16 +0000</created>
                <updated>Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:58:54 +0000</updated>
                            <resolved>Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:58:54 +0000</resolved>
                                                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>5</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="257511" author="pjones" created="Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:58:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Great&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257509" author="jamervi" created="Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:58:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Must have been posting at the same time. I planned to run the fsck this morning, which I did and all is good.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257508" author="jamervi" created="Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:53:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I ran fsck against the file system with the new e2fsprogs first with the preen option which abort and then again with the the &apos;-y&apos; option. After the fsck completed I repeated the &apos;fsck -fy&apos; to ensure it came back clean and remounted the file system.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Everything is good. We can close this issue as resolved.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257507" author="pjones" created="Fri, 1 Nov 2019 16:53:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Am I correct in thinking that we can close this ticket too?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257331" author="ruth.klundt@gmail.com" created="Wed, 30 Oct 2019 14:57:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the confirmation &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt;&#160;I figured so.&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257327" author="adilger" created="Wed, 30 Oct 2019 14:31:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Ruth, sorry but I got the version number wrong. The latest version tagged in our git repo is 1.45.2-wc1. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257283" author="ruth.klundt@gmail.com" created="Tue, 29 Oct 2019 17:35:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The latest e2fsprogs I see is 1.45.2 here:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://downloads.whamcloud.com/public/e2fsprogs/latest/el7/RPMS/x86_64/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://downloads.whamcloud.com/public/e2fsprogs/latest/el7/RPMS/x86_64/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;is there a&#160;1.45.3-wc1 somewhere else?&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257278" author="jamervi" created="Tue, 29 Oct 2019 16:13:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks Andreas. That&apos;s kind of what we though but wanted to make sure. Thanks for the e2fsprogs update recommendation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Peter -&#160;This is through our maintenance support via DDN. Contract was placed on 3/27/19.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257265" author="pjones" created="Tue, 29 Oct 2019 13:28:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Joe&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Is the system in question one of the supported on-prem deployments or our AWS Lustre service without support?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Peter&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="257251" author="adilger" created="Tue, 29 Oct 2019 06:41:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The e2fsck run is looping because it is stuck being told not to fix the inode and also not to stop printing the message. If you run &quot;&lt;tt&gt;e2fsck -fy&lt;/tt&gt;&quot; it will fix the problem by zeroing out the broken inode. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note that it is recommended to run e2fsck from the latest version, which is 1.45.3-wc1 at this time.  It is also a good idea to log the e2fsck output so it is available in. the future if needed. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
